Based on my analysis of the code and test case, I've identified the root cause of the memory error. Let me create a summary:

## ROOT CAUSE

**peglib.h:2563** — When a non-macro rule calls a macro, `FindReference` is initialized with the wrong parameter vector. The line uses `c.rule_stack.back()->params` (the calling rule's parameters) instead of `rule_->params` (the called macro's parameters). This causes a vector size mismatch: when visiting arguments in the loop at line 2842-2843, if `args_.size() > params_.size()`, `params_[i]` accesses out-of-bounds memory.

In the test case:
- Rule `A` (non-macro) calls `B(T)` where `B` is a macro
- When processing the call, `params_` is set to `A.params = []` (empty)
- But `args_` contains `[T]` (size 1)
- The loop `for (size_t i = 0; i < args_.size(); i++)` tries to access `params_[0]` which is out of bounds

## LOCAL FIX

Change line 2563 from:
```cpp
FindReference vis(c.top_args(), c.rule_stack.back()->params);
```

to:
```cpp
FindReference vis(c.top_args(), rule_->params);
```

This ensures `FindReference` uses the parameter names of the **macro being called**, not the current rule, so argument sizes are properly aligned.

## GLOBAL FIX

Add a bounds check in the `FindReference::visit(Reference &ope)` method (line 2841-2850) to prevent out-of-bounds access:
```cpp
inline void FindReference::visit(Reference &ope) {
  for (size_t i = 0; i < args_.size() && i < params_.size(); i++) {
    const auto &name = params_[i];
    if (name == ope.name_) {
      found_ope = args_[i];
      return;
    }
  }
  found_ope = ope.shared_from_this();
}
```

The primary fix (changing to `rule_->params`) addresses the root cause; the secondary bounds check provides defense-in-depth against similar mismatches elsewhere in the codebase.
